in urban development—cities, roads, railways, ports, digital and energy connectivity—are directly linked to its foreign policy goals. Curtis and Klaus examine the implications of these developments as they evolve across the vast Afro-Eurasian region. The distinctive model of international order and urban life emerging with the rise of Chinese power and influence offers a potential rival to the one that has accompanied the rise and zenith of Western power, marking a new age of infrastructural geopolitics and Great Power competition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aUrbanizationzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aKlaus, Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277227?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277227/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles